      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>podcast</strong> is an audio-first content format distributed as on-demand episodes through streaming platforms like Spotify and Apple Podcasts. Listeners subscribe and consume content on their own schedule. According to Edison Research, <strong>144 million Americans — 42% of those aged 12 and older — listened to a podcast in the past month</strong>, making it one of the highest-engagement content channels available to brands.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg. episode length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">30-45 min</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">US monthly listeners</div>
            <div class="tms-value">144 million</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A podcast gives your brand 30-45 uninterrupted minutes with a listener who chose to be there. No algorithm decides whether your episode surfaces — subscribers get every episode automatically. That's the distribution model that makes podcasting genuinely different from social media or blog content.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a podcast?</h2>
        <p>A podcast is a series of audio (or video) episodes made available for streaming or download. The term combines "iPod" and "broadcast," though podcasts have long since moved beyond any single device. They distribute through RSS feeds to every major platform simultaneously — Spotify, Apple Podcasts, Google Podcasts, Amazon Music, and hundreds of smaller aggregators.</p>
        <p>Three characteristics define a podcast versus other audio content:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Episodic structure</strong> — content is published in recurring episodes, not as standalone pieces</li>
          <li><strong>Subscription model</strong> — listeners subscribe and receive new episodes automatically</li>
          <li><strong>On-demand consumption</strong> — listeners choose when and where to listen, typically during commutes, workouts, or household tasks</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Edison Research: The Infinite Dial 2024</div>
          <p>42% of Americans aged 12 and older — roughly <strong>144 million people</strong> — listened to a podcast in the past month. Weekly listeners average <strong>8 episodes per week</strong>, typically consuming content during commutes and exercise.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why podcasts matter for brand-building</h2>
        <p>Podcasts produce a different kind of attention than social or search. Here's why that attention compounds into business results:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Depth of engagement.</strong> Average episode consumption runs 30-45 minutes — 10-20x longer than a blog post read or social media scroll. Listeners who finish your episodes have substantially higher brand recall and trust than those who skim an article.</li>
          <li><strong>Algorithm independence.</strong> A podcast subscriber receives every episode directly. You're not competing for feed visibility or paying for distribution. That relationship is yours.</li>
          <li><strong>Content repurposing multiplier.</strong> One 45-minute interview produces a full transcript, a blog post, 5-10 social clips, quotable pull quotes, and an audiogram. A single recording session can fuel a week of content across all channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Authority positioning.</strong> Hosting a podcast positions you as the person who convenes conversations in your industry. Guests bring their audiences; listeners build a parasocial relationship with your voice and perspective.</li>
          <li><strong>SEO through transcripts.</strong> Episode transcripts published as companion pages create indexable content that ranks for long-tail queries. Local business podcasts have improved map pack visibility by signaling topical depth to Google.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How podcasting works</h2>
        <p>The podcast distribution stack has three layers: production, hosting, and distribution.</p>

        <h3>Production</h3>
        <p>Record with a USB microphone ($50-$100 range) in a quiet room with soft furnishings to reduce echo. Edit using Descript (AI-powered, removes filler words automatically), Adobe Audition, or free tools like Audacity. Export as MP3 at 128kbps for mono recordings or 192kbps for stereo.</p>

        <h3>Hosting</h3>
        <p>Upload episodes to a podcast hosting platform — Buzzsprout, Transistor, or Podbean are common choices at $12-$25 per month. The host generates an RSS feed and handles file storage, analytics, and delivery to distribution platforms.</p>

        <h3>Distribution</h3>
        <p>Submit your RSS feed once to each major platform. Spotify, Apple Podcasts, and Amazon Music then pull new episodes automatically as you publish. Most hosting platforms include one-click submission to all major directories.</p>

