        <h2 id="examples">Real podcast examples by business type</h2>
        <p>Podcasting scales from solo consultants to enterprise brands. These examples illustrate the range:</p>

        <h3>1. Marketing agency — weekly CMO interviews</h3>
        <p>A mid-size agency launched a weekly show interviewing CMOs about their 2026 priorities. After 50 episodes, the show generated 3-5 qualified inbound leads per month from listeners who had been following for months before reaching out. The host credibility from "we interviewed 50 CMOs" became a differentiator in sales conversations.</p>

        <h3>2. Local accountant — 15-minute tax tips</h3>
        <p>A local accounting firm published 15-minute episodes on quarterly tax planning. Episode transcripts published as blog posts improved time-on-page metrics and contributed to local pack ranking improvements for tax-related queries in their city.</p>

        <h3>3. SaaS company — customer stories</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company ran a customer spotlight podcast, inviting users to share how they solved a business problem. Each episode became a case study, a social campaign, and a sales enablement asset — all from one 30-minute conversation.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Podcast vs blog — which content format wins?</h2>
        <p>Both formats serve content marketing but in different ways. The decision should be format-fit, not either/or.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Podcast advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>30-45 minute sustained attention per episode</li>
              <li>Algorithm-free subscription delivery</li>
              <li>Parasocial relationship through voice and personality</li>
              <li>Guest cross-promotion drives new listeners</li>
              <li>Consumed during commutes and exercise (no screen required)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Blog advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Directly indexed by Google — SEO from day one</li>
              <li>Lower production time per piece</li>
              <li>Easier to update and keep evergreen</li>
              <li>Shareable as links, not file downloads</li>
              <li>Works for audiences without audio habits</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for launching a brand podcast</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define a specific audience before recording episode one.</strong> "Marketing professionals" is too broad. "B2B SaaS marketing managers at 50-200 person companies" is a show you can build and a community you can reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Choose your format by growth model, not preference.</strong> Interview formats grow fastest because guests promote episodes to their audiences. If you want fast growth, interview formats outperform solo shows at early stage.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish transcripts on your website.</strong> Episode transcripts create indexable content for Google and provide accessibility for listeners who prefer reading. Host them as blog posts with the embedded audio player.</li>
          <li><strong>Commit to at least 30 episodes before evaluating.</strong> Most podcast analytics are vanity metrics in the first 10 episodes. Business results — leads, partnerships, speaking invitations — emerge after consistent publishing over 6+ months.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose every episode systematically.</strong> One interview produces: a full transcript, a summary blog post, 3-5 short video clips for social, 1-2 pull-quote graphics, and one email newsletter. Build this workflow before you launch.</li>
          <li><strong>Submit to Spotify and Apple Podcasts on day one.</strong> These two platforms account for 80%+ of podcast listening. RSS submission is free and takes under an hour through any major hosting platform.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — publishing without a promotion plan</div>
          <p>The podcast graveyard is full of high-quality shows that nobody found. Production quality matters less than distribution. Before recording episode one, build your promotion playbook: which guests will cross-promote, which email list you'll announce to, and which social channels will feature clips. Promotion is not optional — it is the job.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common podcast mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Publishing monthly</strong> — too infrequent to build listener habits. Weekly or biweekly is the minimum viable cadence.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping transcripts</strong> — leaving SEO value on the table and reducing accessibility for deaf and hard-of-hearing audiences.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic episode titles</strong> — "Episode 43 with John Smith" tells nobody what they'll learn. Titles should describe the insight, not the guest name.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-investing in audio gear before audience</strong> — a $50 USB microphone in a quiet room sounds better than a $500 microphone in an echoey office. Spend money on promotion, not production, until you have 1,000+ downloads per episode.</li>
          <li><strong>No call to action</strong> — every episode should direct listeners to one specific next step: subscribe, visit a landing page, or book a call.</li>
        </ul>

